<dl id="n38060a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38060a">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38060a"> 60(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Dom Butler / Ultramontane</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[review article]</font>: <b>The Vatican Council</b> / Two New Studies / The Vatican Council. By Dom Cuthbert Butler. Two Volumes. (Longmans. 25s. net.) <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Abbot Butler has done a real service to all students of Church history by his clear, fully documented, and honourably impartial account of the Vatican Council, attended by the Bishops of the Roman Catholic Church, which met at the end of 1869 and in the following year proclaimed the doctrine of Papal Infallibility.<font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> The definition of Papal Infallibility <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> marked, as <mark>Dom Butler</mark> allows us to see from his introductory chapters, the culmination of the <mark>Ultramontane</mark> movement in the Roman communion which had for its object to establish the central authority in the Church upon a basis independent of the various national episcopates. <small> <a name="TT27may30" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#TT27may30"><cite title="source">The Times</cite></a> (27 May 1930) 22/4</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
